Reward shaping (env_engine, see RewardWeights + step_with_actions in lib.rs):
    * terminal       = ships_share = own_ships / all_players_ships  (in [0,1]).
                       Replaces the old ±1 win/loss — we no longer care *who*
                       wins, only how much of the board's ships we end with.
                       Shares sum to 1 across players.
    * terminal_time  = ± remaining_turns / episode_steps. + for the winner
                       (max-ships, ties count), − for losers. Rewards fast wins
                       and punishes fast losses: 1/episode_steps per remaining
                       turn, so a turn-1 finish is worth ~±1.0.
    * production_share = 0.001 × own_production / Σ all players' production,
                       per step (neutral excluded; 0 if no player has any). A
                       small dense nudge toward owning more of the board's
                       production. Bounded by ~episode_steps/1000 ≈ 0.5 over a
                       game, and weaker per-turn (1/1000) than terminal_time's
                       fast-win pull (1/500), so it doesn't reintroduce stalling.
(Replaces the old production_delta + launch_penalty terms, which were misleading
and — by penalising launches / rewarding the telescoped prod swing — nudged
toward stalling, counteracting the early-win bonus.)
Validated by env_engine/validate_reward.py: terminal terms recomputed from the
final state and the per-step production_share recomputed from each step's obs,
both checked against the engine's reward_components (incl. early eliminations
that exercise a large remaining fraction).


